@NODE 3. "Introduction"
                            Introduction.

	AmiGSM is a simple application to send SMS messages to GSM phones
	via the Internet. You just select the network the GSM phone is
	located on, type in the phone number, type in a message (Upto a
	MAX 150 chars long, depending on the server), and click on Send.
	
	If all goes well, the message will be sent to the GSM phone with
	the phone number you types in.

@ENDNODE

@NODE 0. "Getting Started"
                           Getting Started.

	Just double click on the AmiGSM icon. A Classact window should
	open on your Workbench screen.
	
	If you use a proxy, edit the AmiGSM.info TOOLTYPES and put
	your proxy host and port in it.
	
	If any required ClassAct classes are missing, AmiGSM will let
	you know and it will then attempt to download the latest classes.

@ENDNODE

@NODE 1. "Configuration"
                         Configuring AmiGSM.

	To configure AmiGSM, select the settings you will use and
	select "Save Config" from the pull down menu.
	
	AmiGSM will save all the data you last used, and window position.
	
	If you are behind a firewall and have to use a proxy server, then
	edit the icon tooltypes PROXY and PORT settings to suit your
	server.
	
	To use the phonebook in AmiGSM, click on the button next to the
	Number gadget.
	To edit the phonebook, select PhoneBook from the Config pulldown
	menu. Add, delete, or modify as you see fit.
	
@ENDNODE

@NODE 2. "Usage"
                          Using AmiGSM.

	The GUI is simple in design for ease of use.
	
	To send a message to a GSM phone:
	
	o Select the network the phone is located on.
	o Type in the phone number for that phone.
	o Type in a message (MAX 160 chars) AmiGSM wont allow you to enter
	  over 160 characters, depending on the server used.
	o Click on Send.
	
	If all goes well, the message will be sent.

@ENDNODE

@NODE 6. "Networks"
                    Networks supported by AmiGSM.

	MTN South Africa (www.mtn.co.za)
	   Global coverage for over 35 countries.
	   Upto 150 character messages. (100 in demo version)
	   Limited to 10 messages per day per number.

	Vodacom South Africa (www.vodacom.co.za)
	   Limited coverage to vodacom network.
	   Upto 150 character messages. (100 in demo version)

	Omnipoint United States (www.omnipoint.com)
	   Limited coverage to omnipoint network.
	   Upto 60 character messages (22 in demo version)
	   Limited to 30 messages per month per number.

	If you have a local SMS network that isn't supported in AmiGSM,
	phone your dealer and ask them if they support a web based SMS
	message service.
	If they do email me the URL to the page that SUBMITS the message
	and I will see about supporting it in a future version.

@ENDNODE

@NODE 4. "Requirements"
                            Requirements.

	Classact 2.0. (AmiGSM will download the latest classes if you
	               havent got them installed.)

	Internet account.

@ENDNODE

@NODE 5. "Arexx"
                           Arexx commands.

	AmiGSM Arexx Port name: AMIGSM
	
	Arexx Commands:
	                  PREFIX - The international prefix. Eg, +61414 is
	                           Australia Vodaphone.
	                  NUMBER - The phone number of the phone you want to
	                           message.
	                  MSG    - The message you want to send. (Limited
	                           to 150 chars)
	                  SEND   - Send the message.
	                  QUIT   - Quit AmiGSM.
	                  NOGUI  - Start AmiGSM without the GUI.

	See the included AmiGSM.rexx for an example. (Use the "NOGUI" CLI
	ARG if you don't want AmiGSM to open with a GUI)

@ENDNODE

